Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Trim the @green beans{80} then chop into thirds. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Cut the @halloumi{250%g} in half through the middle, then cut into 2cm chunks.

Pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, add @salt{0.25%tsp}, stir in the @basmati rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the green beans and stir fry until slightly browned and almost tender, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add half the @garlic clove{1}(minced), cook for another ~{30%seconds}, remove the beans to a #large bowl{}.

Put your pan back on high heat, add a drizzle of oil if the pan is dry. Add the halloumi, fry until golden on all sides, turning often, ~{3-5%minutes} total (cook in batches if you need to). Remove from the pan to the bowl with the beans. Put your pan back on medium heat with a little more oil, add the onion. Stir fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}, then add the @mild curry powder{1%tbsp}, stir and cook for ~{30%seconds}.

Add the @tomato puree{30%g} and remaining garlic. Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}. Pour the @tomato passata{1%250ml bottle} and @water{150%ml} for the curry into the pan with the onion, bring to the boil then gently stir in three quarters of the @mango chutney{40%g}, all the green beans and all the halloumi. Add a grind of @pepper{grind}, bring back to the boil again then reduce the heat to medium low. Simmer until the mixture has reduced slightly, ~{6-8%minutes}. Stir every couple of mins.

While everything finishes cooking, put the rest of the mango chutney in a #bowl{} and add the @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g} and a grind of pepper. Stir together. Once the rice is cooked, fluff it up with a #fork{} and spoon into #bowls{}. Taste the curry and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it, add a splash of water too if it's a bit thick for your liking. Spoon it on top of the rice and finish with a drizzle of yoghurt. Enjoy!

> We love a good Halloumi Curry with Rice and this deliciously simple, chef-curated recipe doesn't disappoint. Time to bust out the pots and pans!